<hl>
<seg id=1> Bangkok's elevated railroad project will restart. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (Bangkok) Yesterday, The Thailand Ministry of Transportation announced that, Thailand is going to request the amount of 6.8 billion US dollars (about 11 billion New Yuan) from the Hopewell Group, since the Hong Kong company that undertook the project of constructing Bangkok's elevated railroad, has failed to accomplish the contract on time. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Perladi, the Vice Minister of Thailand's Ministry of Transportation said that, Thailand's Ministry of Transportation and the National Railway Bureau have the right to seek 6.8 billion US dollars compensation. Thailand blames the Hopewell Group for only finishing 12% of the original plan during the past 8 years. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> The Hopewell Group was drawn into financial and land confiscation entanglements due to Thailand currency's depreciation after economy conjuncture in Thailand, and several negotiations had failed with the Thailand government. The Thailand government had already called off the contract with the Hopewell Group in January this year. </seg>
<seg id=5> Therefore, the Hopewell Group requested amends of 100 billion Thai Baht (about 4.2 billion new Yuan) from the Thailand government. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> The Thai government said yesterday that the Thai plan to restart this 3.2 billion US dollar project, however they will consider reducing the size of the project. </seg>
<seg id=7> The Hopewell Group will not be involved in this project no matter what. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> Perladi said that the German Government and the KFW Bank are interested in continuing this project and have already provided 100,000,000 Baht for research into feasibility studies for the Bangkok elevated railway and other road projects. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> The German Shermans Company is currently working together with a local company constructing a 23 Kilometer electronic train engineering project. </seg>
</p>
